To add a footnote to the list of authors in LaTeX, you can use the `\footnotemark` command and the `\footnotetext` command. Here's how you can do it:

1. Write the authors' names and affiliations as usual in your LaTeX document. For example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{natbib}

\begin{document}

\title{My Research Paper}
\author{John Doe\thanks{This work was supported by the National Science Foundation.}}
\author{Jane Smith}
\author{Bob Johnson\thanks{This work was also supported by the National Science Foundation.}}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}

\cite{doe2012research,smith2013study,johnson2014analysis}

\bibliographystyle{plainnat}
\bibliography{mybibfile}

\end{document}
```

2. Add the footnotes to the authors' names using the `\thanks` command inside the curly braces `{}` after the author's name. For example:

```latex
\author{John Doe\thanks{This work was supported by the National Science Foundation.}}
\author{Jane Smith}
\author{Bob Johnson\thanks{This work was also supported by the National Science Foundation.}}
```

3. Add the footnote text using the `\footnotetext` command after the `\maketitle` command. For example:

```latex
\footnotetext[1]{This work was supported by the National Science Foundation.}
\footnotetext[2]{This work was also supported by the National Science Foundation.}
```

The numbers inside the square brackets `[ ]` correspond to the numbers inside the curly braces `{ }` after the authors' names.

4. Compile the LaTeX document to see the footnotes appear at the bottom of the first page, next to the authors' names.

That's it! You've added footnotes to the list of authors in LaTeX.
